	<div id="content">
		<div id="red">
			<h2 class="inlineh2" id="postitle">
				DEVICE INTERACTION GARNERING HUMAN INTERACTION
			</h2>
			<div class="inline">
				<div class="column">
					<h3 class=paratitle>
						UID Yearly events are often home to an anxious lot. With this in mind, and in order to engage
						the public in a pop-up exhibition, we designed
						the UID Devices.
					</h3>
				</div>
				<div class="column"></div>

			</div>

			<div class="inline">
				<div class="column">
					<h2 class="inlineh2">
						THE USERS
					</h2>
					<h3 class=paratitle>
						People attending UID'15. Especially students presenting thesis projects, or people
						eager to network, that might be feeling anxious and stage-frightened.
					</h3>
				</div>
				<div class="column">

				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="inline">
				<div class="column">
					<h2 class="inlineh2">
						THE NEEDS
					</h2>
					<h3 class=paratitle>
						Having had presentation classes (and classes with presentations) throughout the year,
						we were able to spot common afflictions to a person speaking publicly.
					</h3>
				</div>
				<div class="column">

				</div>
			</div>

			<h2 class="inlineh2">
				IDEATION
			</h2>
			<div class="inline" id="preimg">
				<div class="column">
					<h3 class=paratitle>
						We chose three question that seemed the most common: How do I look? Am I being heard? Are my
						hands shaking?
						If people could have an answer to these questions, perhaps they'd be a little less
						anxious before presenting or talking to someone.
					</h3>
				</div>
				<div class="column"></div>

			</div>

			<div class="inline" id="preimg">
				<div class="column">
					<h2 class="inlineh2">
						CONCEPT
					</h2>
					<h3 class=paratitle>
						The main attributes for the devices "personality" were guided by the needs of the public:
						anxious users would benefit from <span id="green">soothing and reassuring answers</span>; <span
							id="pink">funny</span> answers could also help to break the ice. At the same time, these
						answers should <span id="yellow">spark interaction</span> between atendess.

						<br><br>
						This attributes are reached by the design through the semantics of the given answers: they're
						reassuring because <span id="green">"low markings" are delivered with a kind tone</span>; also,
						the hyperbolic
						nature of the <span id="pink">"top markings" are non-sensical and fun</span>. The <span
							id="yellow">gamification of the ranking system</span> sparks interaction between atendees,
						as they feel compelled to "challenge" each other.
					</h3>
				</div>
				<div class="column">
					<h2 id="spanh2"><span id="green">REASSURING</span>,</h2>
					<h2 id="spanh2"><span id="pink">FUNNY</span> + </h2>
					<h2 id="spanh2"><span id="yellow">SPARK INTERACTION</span></h2>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="inline3">
				<div class="column3">
					<img class="img" src="../images/voiceinspectorCrop.jpg"></img>
					<h3 class="paratitlecenter">NO. 1 - Voice Inspector
					</h3>
					<p class="text">
						Built with a microhpone inside, it ranks the volume of the voice of a person talking in front of
						it.
						The minimum value - "lovely whisper" - aims to be kind instead of accusing.

					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="column3">
					<img class="img" src="../images/looksinspectorCrop.jpg"></img>
					<h3 class="paratitlecenter">NO. 2 - Looks Inspector
					</h3>
					<p class="text">
						With a presence detector and a mirror, it tells the person standing in front of it wheter he
						or she look OK. In fact, it only randomly blinks green or yellow (67% and 33% odds), but the
						red was kept there so people can feel reassured they didn't get it.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="column3">
					<img class="img" src="../images/stressinspectorCrop.jpg"></img>
					<h3 class="paratitlecenter">NO. 3 - Stress inspector</h3>
					<p class="text">
						A game where the user tries to bring the key from one end of the rail to the other without
						touching,
						and can check his or her score along the markings, to compare and challenge others.

					</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<!-- triple inline here -->

			<h2 class="inlineh2" id="postitle">
				EXECUTION
			</h2>
			<div class="inline" id="preimg">
				<div class="column">
					<h3 class=paratitle>
						The devices were hung on the entrance foyer wall of the Umea Institute of Design during it's
						annual event in 2015: UID'15. The video below documents the process as well as the public
						response
						to them.
					</h3>
				</div>
				<div class="column"></div>
			</div>


		</div>
		<iframe width="1280" height="720" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/7UExyGUW9SI?rel=0" frameborder="0"
			allowfullscreen></iframe>
		<p class="text"></p>
		<div class=divider></div>
		<div class=subdivider></div>

		<h2 id="conclusion">ROLE IN THE PROJECT AND FINAL THOUGHTS</h2>
		<h3 class=paratitlecenter>The project was done during the Industrial Design Intensive programme at UID, by me
			and Felix Noller.</h3>
		<p class="text">
			The inception of the devices came from Felix, who then approached me to tinker the concept together. Later,
			Felix handled the Arduino programming and I took care
			of the witty labelling for the scores, as well as the closing circuit game. With the footage captured
			by both of us, I edited the project video on Blender.
		</p>
		<div class=divider></div>
		<div class=subdivider></div>
	</div>















INOVA













	<div id="content">
		<h2>
			FUTURISTIC,<br />"FLOATING"<br />FLATWARE
		</h2>
		<h3 class=paratitlecenter>
			Inova Diamond is a flatware series designed for a large brazilian manufacturer.
		</h3>
		<p class="text">The Inova line bestows the feature of preventing the blade of the silverware from
			touching the surface beneath it. The Diamond models, thus, keep such feature while being
			reshaped with a completely different design language. The main goal of this project
			was to aid the manufacturer to position a simple, low cost polymer flatware
			as innovative and premium.
		</p>
		<p class="imgholder01" id="img01"><img id="renderCinza" src="../images/renderCinzaSombra.png"></img></p>
		<div class=divider></div>
		<div class=subdivider></div>
		<div id=red>
			<h2 class=inlineh2>
				DESIGNING THE DIAMOND
			</h2>
			<div class=inline>
				<div class=column>
					<img class="img" id="diamondBack" src="../images/diamondBack.png"></img>
				</div>
				<div class=column>
					<h3 class=paratitle>The geometric lines culminate in the diamond-shaped back of the grip</h3>
					<p class="imgtext">The reasoning behind choosing a mostly geometric, polygonal design language was
						to deviate from <a href="../images/inovadplus.png">the previous Inova line</a>, and most similar
						products for that matter,
						that employ curved, organic forms on the grips. It has a similar mass to its predecessor, not
						increasing manufacturing costs.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class=inline>
				<div class=column id=blowup>
					<img class="imgliquid" src="../images/trianglesMedium.png"></img>
					<div class=pointer id=pointer01>
						<hr>
						<p>a</p>
					</div>
					<div class=pointer id=pointer02>
						<hr>
						<p>b</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class=column>
					<h3 class=paratitle>Organic doesn't necessarily mean "ergonomic", and vice-versa</h3>
					<p class="imgtext">During the ideation phase, the main theoretical touchstone was brazilian
						ergonomist Itiro Iida's chapter on
						grips and small utensils, where it's pointed out that while geometrically shaped grips
						might not seem anatomical at first, they are well suited for longer handling periods
						with low force exertion, because they allow for multiple hand positions (more
						anatomically resembling grips, however, are better suited for shorter, higher force usage)
						<a href=#references>[1]</a>. A live example of such concept is <a
							href="http://konstantin-grcic.com/resources/534.jpg">the chair _ONE</a>, by Konstantin
						Grcic.<br><br>The dimensions of faces (a) and (b) - the only in contact with the surface below -
						were
						finetuned through several rapid prototyping iterations, to find the optimal trade-off between
						stability
						and handling comfort.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class=imgholder02><img class="img" src="../images/prototipos10.jpg"></img></div>
			<h3 class=paratitlecenter>Prototyping was crucial to find a pleasant grip that still wouldn't tumble over
			</h3>
			<p class="text">The sequential iterations of the grip design (from top to bottom) were 3D printed in two
				halves, and had blades provided by the manufacturer attached to one end.
				The last one, in black, is an injection test. The prototypes were then brought to lunch at restaurants,
				to be tested.
			</p>
			<div class=divider></div>
			<div class=subdivider></div>
		</div>
		<div class=imgholder01 id="inovaFull"><img class="img" src="../images/produzido.jpg"></img>
			<p class=caption><span>The manufactured product was showcased on the House and Gift Fair 2015, in S&atildeo
					Paulo</span></p>
		</div>
		<h2>ROLE IN THE PROJECT AND FINAL THOUGHTS</h2>
		<h3 class=paratitlecenter>Inova Diamond was the project at which I had the most independence as an intern at
			Grupo Criativo</h3>
		<p class="text">Of the design projects I took part during my internship (ranging from food trays to etnography
			research of artisanal bakers) the Diamond was the longest.
			I believe it was so especially due to the incentive from coworkers, among them my supervisor, Gabriel
			Altenhofen, who had designed the previous Inova model, to see how far the design could be pushed and
			finetuned.
			Eventhough the ideation and modelling were done mostly solo, input from the team was always present and
			taken into consideration (such as turning the diamond up, when originally it was inverted). Gabriel was
			responsible for finetuning the
			fillets on the six-edge vertex on the bottom side of the grip, that demanded special attention.
		</p>
		<h3 class=paratitlecenter id=references>REFERENCES</h3>
		<p class=text>[1] ITIRO IIDA, Ergonomia: Projeto e Produ&ccedil&atildeo, 2005</p>
